insert into public.concepts
  (id, term, aliases, said, alias_list, status, one_liner, analogy, example, related, deeper, lens_pm, lens_eng, domain, priority, tags)
values
  ('diffusionmodel', 'Diffusion Model', '', '', ARRAY['diffusionmodel','diffusion model','diffusion models']::text[], 'Core', 'A model that learns to make images by starting from pure static and cleaning it up step by step.', 'Like watching a photo develop in a darkroom tray, except it runs backwards from noise toward a picture.', 'When you type a prompt into an image generator and watch a fuzzy blob sharpen into a cat over a few seconds, that’s a diffusion model at work.', '[{"text":"The specific training recipe most diffusion models use.","id":"denoisingdiffusion"},{"text":"The older rival it largely displaced for image generation.","id":"gan"}]'::jsonb, 'Training teaches it to predict the noise that was added to a real image; run that predictor in reverse many times and you turn random noise into a coherent picture. Each step removes a little noise, guided by your text prompt. It’s slower than a single forward pass, which is why image generation takes seconds, not milliseconds.', 'The reason text-to-image tools feel magical and also why they cost real compute per picture.', 'A generative model trained to reverse a fixed noising process, sampling iteratively from noise to data.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('denoisingdiffusion', 'Denoising Diffusion', '', '', ARRAY['denoisingdiffusion','denoising diffusion','ddpm']::text[], 'Core', 'The exact recipe behind diffusion models: add noise on purpose, then train a network to take it back out.', 'Like deliberately smudging a drawing and teaching an apprentice to un-smudge it one pass at a time.', 'The 2020 DDPM paper turned this into the standard training loop that powers today’s image and video generators.', '[{"text":"The model class this recipe builds.","id":"diffusionmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'You corrupt training images with Gaussian noise across many steps until they’re unrecognizable, then train the model to predict what noise was added at each step. Generation runs the same steps in reverse. The whole thing is a clever way to break an impossibly hard “make an image” problem into thousands of tiny, learnable “remove a little noise” problems.', 'The underlying method you’re licensing whenever you buy into an image or video model.', 'A latent-variable model where the forward process is fixed Gaussian noising and the reverse process is learned.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('gan', 'GAN', 'Generative Adversarial Network', '', ARRAY['gan','gans','generative adversarial network']::text[], 'Fading', 'Two networks in a duel: one fakes images, the other calls out fakes, and both get sharper.', 'A forger and a detective locked in a room — each pushes the other to get better until the forgeries pass.', 'The eerily realistic faces on “thispersondoesnotexist” were GAN output, back when GANs ruled image generation.', '[{"text":"The full name spelled out.","id":"generativeadversarialnetwork"},{"text":"The method that largely replaced it.","id":"diffusionmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'A generator invents images and a discriminator judges real vs. fake; training pits them against each other until the generator’s fakes fool the judge. It produces crisp results but is notoriously unstable to train and prone to “mode collapse,” where it churns out the same few images. Diffusion models have mostly taken over because they’re steadier.', 'A once-dominant approach now mostly of historical and niche interest for generation.', 'A minimax game between a generator and discriminator, trained to a Nash equilibrium.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('generativeadversarialnetwork', 'Generative Adversarial Network', 'GAN', '', ARRAY['generativeadversarialnetwork']::text[], 'Fading', 'The full name for a GAN — a generator and a critic trained by competing against each other.', 'Counterfeiter versus bank teller: the better the teller gets at spotting fakes, the better the counterfeiter has to be.', 'Ian Goodfellow’s 2014 paper introduced the idea and set off years of photorealistic-face research.', '[{"text":"The common abbreviation and its story.","id":"gan"}]'::jsonb, 'The generator maps random noise to fake data; the discriminator learns to separate fakes from real samples. Their opposing objectives create a moving target that, when it works, produces sharp samples — and when it doesn’t, collapses or oscillates. The adversarial framing was the big idea; the training pain was the price.', 'Historically important, but you’ll rarely reach for it in a new product today.', 'Same as GAN: adversarial training of paired generator and discriminator networks.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('vae', 'VAE', 'Variational Autoencoder', '', ARRAY['vae','vaes','variational autoencoder']::text[], 'Core', 'An autoencoder that compresses data into a smooth, organized space you can sample new things from.', 'Like a librarian who not only files every book but arranges the shelves so similar books sit together — so you can wander to a nearby spot and find something plausible.', 'Most modern image diffusion models actually run inside a VAE’s compressed space to save compute, not on raw pixels.', '[{"text":"The plain version without the probabilistic twist.","id":"autoencoder"},{"text":"The generative method it often compresses for.","id":"diffusionmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'It squeezes input into a probability distribution over a small latent space, then decodes samples back out. The “variational” part forces that latent space to be smooth and continuous, so nearby points decode to similar outputs and you can generate new samples by sampling the space. Outputs tend to be blurrier than GANs or diffusion, but the tidy latent space is the payoff.', 'Often the invisible compression layer that makes big image models affordable to run.', 'An autoencoder with a KL-regularized latent distribution, trained on a reconstruction-plus-divergence objective.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('variationalautoencoder', 'Variational Autoencoder', 'VAE', '', ARRAY['variationalautoencoder']::text[], 'Core', 'The full name for a VAE — an autoencoder whose middle is a smooth, sampleable space.', 'A vending machine that not only stores snacks but lays them out so you can dial to a spot between two and get a sensible blend.', 'When a latent-diffusion image model “decodes” its result to pixels, that decoder is a VAE’s.', '[{"text":"The everyday short name.","id":"vae"}]'::jsonb, 'It learns to encode inputs as distributions rather than single points, and a regularization term keeps that latent space continuous and well-behaved. That lets you generate by sampling and interpolate between examples smoothly. The trade-off is softer, less crisp reconstructions than adversarial or diffusion approaches.', 'The quiet workhorse compressing data so pricier generative steps stay cheap.', 'Identical to VAE: variational inference over a latent code with an encoder–decoder pair.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('autoencoder', 'Autoencoder', '', '', ARRAY['autoencoder','autoencoders','auto-encoder']::text[], 'Core', 'A network that learns to squeeze data down and rebuild it, keeping only what matters.', 'Like zipping a file and unzipping it — if the copy still looks right, the middle captured the essence.', 'A denoising autoencoder can take a grainy scan, compress it, and reconstruct a clean version.', '[{"text":"The probabilistic, generative descendant.","id":"vae"},{"text":"What the bottleneck produces.","id":"representation"}]'::jsonb, 'An encoder shrinks the input into a small “bottleneck” representation, and a decoder tries to reconstruct the original from it. Because the bottleneck is smaller than the input, the network is forced to keep the important structure and drop the noise. It’s used for compression, denoising, and learning useful representations — the ancestor of the VAE.', 'A simple building block for compression, cleanup, and feature learning.', 'An encoder–decoder trained to minimize reconstruction error through a low-dimensional bottleneck.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('unet', 'U-Net', '', '', ARRAY['unet','u-net','u net']::text[], 'Core', 'A U-shaped network that shrinks an image down, then grows it back — with shortcuts across the U so detail survives.', 'Like sketching the big shapes first, then zooming back in with your original reference photo taped beside you so you don’t lose the fine lines.', 'The denoising step inside most image diffusion models is a U-Net predicting what noise to remove.', '[{"text":"The generative process it usually powers.","id":"diffusionmodel"},{"text":"The shortcut trick it relies on.","id":"skipconnection"}]'::jsonb, 'The downsampling half captures context (what’s in the picture), the upsampling half restores resolution (where exactly), and skip connections pass fine-grained detail directly across the U so it isn’t lost in the squeeze. Born in medical image segmentation, it became the default backbone for diffusion because it’s good at pixel-precise prediction.', 'The engine room of most image generators, even if users never hear the name.', 'An encoder–decoder CNN with symmetric skip connections between matching resolution levels.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('resnet', 'ResNet', 'Residual Network', '', ARRAY['resnet','resnets','residual network']::text[], 'Core', 'The network that let us stack layers really deep by giving each one a shortcut around itself.', 'Like an express lane on a highway — if a stretch of road adds nothing, traffic can just skip past it untouched.', 'ResNet-50 is still a default image backbone in production vision systems years after its 2015 debut.', '[{"text":"The shortcut idea at its heart.","id":"residualconnection"},{"text":"The image-model family it belongs to.","id":"convolutionalneuralnetwork"}]'::jsonb, 'Very deep networks used to get worse, not better, because the training signal faded on its way back through dozens of layers. ResNet added “residual” shortcuts that let each layer learn only the change it needs, with the input passed through untouched by default. That single trick unlocked networks hundreds of layers deep and reshaped everything after.', 'A durable, battle-tested vision backbone you can still ship on today.', 'A CNN with identity skip connections so layers learn residual functions, easing gradient flow.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('bert', 'BERT', 'Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers', '', ARRAY['bert','berts']::text[], 'Fading', 'An encoder that reads a whole sentence in both directions at once to understand it — great at reading, not built for writing.', 'Like a proofreader who scans the entire sentence before judging any one word, rather than reading strictly left to right.', 'For years, Google Search used BERT to better grasp what a query actually meant.', '[{"text":"The masking task it trains on.","id":"maskedlanguagemodel"},{"text":"The half of the transformer it uses.","id":"encoderonly"}]'::jsonb, 'BERT is encoder-only: it looks at all the words at once (bidirectional) and is trained by masking random words and predicting them. That makes it excellent at classification, search, and understanding tasks, but it can’t naturally generate long text the way a decoder-based model does. Generative LLMs eventually stole the spotlight, but BERT-style encoders still quietly power a lot of search and retrieval.', 'A cheap, fast option when you need to understand or classify text, not write it.', 'An encoder-only transformer pretrained with masked-language-modeling and next-sentence objectives.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('gptarchitecture', 'GPT Architecture', '', '', ARRAY['gptarchitecture','gpt architecture','decoder-only transformer']::text[], 'Core', 'The decoder-only transformer that predicts the next word, over and over — the shape behind most chatbots.', 'Like a storyteller who only ever thinks about the very next word, but does it so well the whole story hangs together.', 'Every model in the GPT, Claude, and Llama families shares this same basic decoder-only skeleton.', '[{"text":"The core prediction task.","id":"nexttokenprediction"},{"text":"The half of the transformer it uses.","id":"decoder"},{"text":"The reading-focused counterpart.","id":"bert"}]'::jsonb, 'It’s a stack of transformer decoder blocks that only look leftward — each position can attend to earlier tokens but not future ones — trained purely to predict the next token. That single simple objective, scaled up massively, turned out to produce fluent writing, reasoning, and code. The architecture barely changed; the scale and data did.', 'The default shape of the generative models your product is probably built on.', 'A causal, decoder-only transformer trained autoregressively on next-token prediction.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('t5', 'T5', 'Text-to-Text Transfer Transformer', '', ARRAY['t5','text-to-text transfer transformer']::text[], 'Fading', 'A model that treats every task — translation, summarizing, answering — as turning one string of text into another.', 'Like a universal adapter that insists everything, from questions to translations, plugs into the same text-in, text-out socket.', 'To classify a review, you’d feed T5 “sentiment: this movie was great” and it outputs the word “positive.”', '[{"text":"The two-part structure it uses.","id":"encoderdecoder"}]'::jsonb, 'T5 uses the full encoder–decoder transformer and reframes every NLP task as text-to-text, so one model and one training setup handle them all. That uniformity made it a clean research workhorse. Decoder-only chat models later showed you could get similar generality without the encoder, but the “everything is text-to-text” framing stuck around.', 'An elegant older approach; most new work uses decoder-only models instead.', 'An encoder–decoder transformer casting all tasks in a unified text-to-text format.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('attentionisallyouneed', 'Attention Is All You Need', '', '', ARRAY['attentionisallyouneed','attention is all you need']::text[], 'Historical', 'The 2017 paper that introduced the transformer and quietly set off the whole modern AI boom.', 'Like the patent for the printing press — modest in the moment, era-defining in hindsight.', 'Nearly every large language model you use traces its lineage directly to this one paper.', '[{"text":"The architecture it introduced.","id":"transformer"},{"text":"The mechanism it championed.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'It showed you could drop the recurrent networks everyone relied on and build a language model purely out of attention, which processes all positions in parallel and scales far better. The title was a cheeky claim that turned out to be right. It’s “historical” only in the sense that its ideas are now everywhere — the paper itself remains foundational.', 'The origin story worth knowing when you talk about why any of this works.', 'The paper introducing the transformer, replacing recurrence with self-attention.', 'Architectures', 10, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('reasoningmodel', 'Reasoning Model', '', '', ARRAY['reasoningmodel','reasoning model','reasoning llm']::text[], 'Rising', 'A model trained to think out loud before answering, spending extra compute to work through hard problems.', 'Like a student who scribbles working on scratch paper instead of blurting the first answer that comes to mind.', 'Ask one a tricky math or coding problem and it’ll generate a long internal chain of steps before giving you the final line.', '[{"text":"The reasoning trace it produces.","id":"chainofthought"},{"text":"The compute-at-answer-time idea it embodies.","id":"testtimecompute"}]'::jsonb, 'These models are trained — often with reinforcement learning — to produce extended reasoning traces, then land on an answer. The longer they “think” at inference time, the better they tend to do on hard tasks, which is a real trade of latency and cost for accuracy. It’s a shift from spending all your compute on training to spending some at answer time.', 'Better on genuinely hard tasks, but slower and pricier per query — pick where it earns its keep.', 'A model post-trained to allocate test-time compute to explicit multi-step reasoning before answering.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('treeofthought', 'Tree of Thought', '', '', ARRAY['treeofthought','tree of thought','tree-of-thoughts','tot']::text[], 'Rising', 'Letting a model branch into several lines of reasoning and explore them like a decision tree instead of one straight path.', 'Like planning a chess move by imagining several candidate moves and their follow-ups, not just the first one you see.', 'For a logic puzzle, the model proposes a few possible first steps, evaluates each, and pursues the most promising branch.', '[{"text":"The single-path version it extends.","id":"chainofthought"}]'::jsonb, 'Where plain chain-of-thought commits to a single reasoning path, tree of thought generates multiple candidate steps, scores them, and can backtrack from dead ends. It trades a lot more compute for better results on problems that need search or planning. It’s more a prompting-and-orchestration strategy than a change to the model’s weights.', 'A way to squeeze harder problems out of a model, at a steep compute multiplier.', 'A search procedure over branching reasoning steps with evaluation and backtracking.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('testtimecompute', 'Test-Time Compute', '', '', ARRAY['testtimecompute','test-time compute','test time compute']::text[], 'Rising', 'Spending more computing power at the moment of answering — not during training — to get a better answer.', 'Like giving yourself more time on an exam question instead of studying harder beforehand — more thinking now, right when it counts.', 'A reasoning model that takes 30 seconds and writes pages of internal steps for a hard proof is burning test-time compute.', '[{"text":"A near-synonym emphasizing the scaling angle.","id":"inferencetimescaling"},{"text":"The model type built around it.","id":"reasoningmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'For years, gains came from bigger models and more training. Test-time compute flips some of that: keep the model fixed but let it think longer, sample more candidates, or search over options at answer time. On hard problems this buys real accuracy, but it directly raises latency and cost per request, so it’s a dial to spend deliberately.', 'A new cost lever — you can now trade money-per-answer for quality, live.', 'Allocating additional inference-time computation (longer generations, sampling, search) to improve outputs.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('inferencetimescaling', 'Inference-Time Scaling', '', '', ARRAY['inferencetimescaling','inference-time scaling','inference time scaling']::text[], 'Rising', 'The finding that answers keep improving the more compute you let a model spend while answering.', 'Like turning up a car’s power by flooring the accelerator in the moment, rather than rebuilding the engine.', 'Charts showing accuracy climbing as a model is allowed to generate longer and longer reasoning are inference-time scaling curves.', '[{"text":"The mechanism it names.","id":"testtimecompute"},{"text":"The training-time counterpart.","id":"scalinglaws"}]'::jsonb, 'It’s the answer-time cousin of training scaling laws: instead of “bigger model, better model,” it’s “more thinking per question, better answer.” This reframed how labs chase performance, since a smaller model with generous inference budget can rival a bigger one on some tasks. The catch is that every extra bit of thinking costs money and time on every single query.', 'Means a modest model can punch above its weight if you’re willing to pay per answer.', 'The empirical scaling of task performance with inference-time compute budget.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('expertrouting', 'Expert Routing', '', '', ARRAY['expertrouting','expert routing']::text[], 'Rising', 'The traffic cop inside a mixture-of-experts model that sends each token to just a few specialized sub-networks.', 'Like a hospital triage nurse deciding which specialist each patient should see, so nobody wastes the whole staff on one case.', 'In a mixture-of-experts model, routing might send a coding token to two “code” experts and skip the other sixty.', '[{"text":"The model type it lives inside.","id":"mixtureofexperts"},{"text":"The small network that makes the choice.","id":"gatingnetwork"}]'::jsonb, 'Instead of every token passing through every parameter, a router picks a small subset of “experts” per token, so the model can be huge in total but cheap per token. Getting the routing right is the hard part — bad routing overloads some experts and starves others. It’s the mechanism that makes sparse giant models practical to run.', 'Why some “huge” models are still affordable to serve — most of them stays idle per query.', 'The learned assignment of tokens to a top-k subset of experts in an MoE layer.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('gatingnetwork', 'Gating Network', '', '', ARRAY['gatingnetwork','gating network','gate network']::text[], 'Rising', 'The little module that scores the experts and decides which ones handle each token.', 'Like a maitre d’ reading the room and deciding which chef should cook each order.', 'When an MoE layer picks its top two experts for a token, the gating network produced those scores.', '[{"text":"The decision it performs.","id":"expertrouting"},{"text":"Another name for essentially the same part.","id":"routernetwork"}]'::jsonb, 'It takes the token’s representation and outputs a weight for each expert, and the top few weights decide who runs and how much their output counts. Training has to keep it from favoring the same experts every time, usually with load-balancing penalties. Small as it is, the gating network shapes whether the whole mixture works or collapses onto a handful of overworked experts.', 'A tiny component whose quality quietly determines whether a big sparse model behaves.', 'A learned softmax-scored selector assigning per-token weights to experts, with load-balancing losses.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('routernetwork', 'Router Network', '', '', ARRAY['routernetwork','router network','router']::text[], 'Rising', 'Another name for the gating module — it routes each token to its chosen experts.', 'Like a mailroom sorter reading each envelope and dropping it in the right department’s bin.', 'A model card might note the router sends each token to two of its many experts.', '[{"text":"The other common name for it.","id":"gatingnetwork"},{"text":"The routing decision itself.","id":"expertrouting"}]'::jsonb, '“Router” and “gating network” usually point at the same thing: the component that decides which experts process a token. The word “router” emphasizes the dispatch, “gating” the weighting. Both must balance load across experts and route consistently, or the model wastes capacity and trains poorly.', 'Same idea as the gating network, described from the dispatch angle.', 'The MoE component computing per-token expert assignments and dispatch weights.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('tokenizerfree', 'Tokenizer-Free', '', '', ARRAY['tokenizerfree','tokenizer-free','tokenizer free']::text[], 'Rising', 'A model that skips the usual word-chopping step and works straight from raw bytes or characters.', 'Like reading a book letter by letter instead of first breaking it into a fixed dictionary of word-pieces.', 'A tokenizer-free model can handle a weird emoji sequence or a rare language script without choking on “unknown token.”', '[{"text":"A concrete instance of the idea.","id":"bytelevelmodel"},{"text":"The step it removes.","id":"tokenization"}]'::jsonb, 'Normal models first split text into subword tokens using a fixed vocabulary, which struggles with rare words, typos, and unusual scripts. Tokenizer-free models operate on bytes or characters directly, gaining robustness and language-fairness at the cost of longer sequences and more compute. It’s an active bet that removing the brittle tokenizer step is worth the extra cost.', 'Promises better handling of messy, multilingual, or noisy text — still an emerging trade-off.', 'A model operating directly on bytes/characters, eliminating a fixed subword vocabulary.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('bytelevelmodel', 'Byte-Level Model', '', '', ARRAY['bytelevelmodel','byte-level model','byte level model']::text[], 'Rising', 'A model that treats text as a raw stream of bytes, so nothing is ever “out of vocabulary.”', 'Like a scanner that reads any document as pixels — it never trips over a font or symbol it hasn’t seen.', 'A byte-level model can process a garbled log file full of odd characters without special handling.', '[{"text":"The broader family it belongs to.","id":"tokenizerfree"}]'::jsonb, 'Every piece of text is ultimately bytes, so a byte-level model has a tiny fixed alphabet and can represent literally anything — code, emoji, any language. The price is much longer sequences, since a word becomes many bytes, which strains attention and speed. Architectural tricks that group bytes internally are how researchers try to keep it affordable.', 'Maximum robustness to weird input, paid for in sequence length and compute.', 'A model with a byte vocabulary, trading a fixed small alphabet for longer sequences.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('hybridarchitecture', 'Hybrid Architecture', '', '', ARRAY['hybridarchitecture','hybrid architecture','hybrid model']::text[], 'Rising', 'A model that mixes different building blocks — say attention plus state-space layers — to get the best of each.', 'Like a hybrid car pairing an electric motor with a gas engine, using whichever suits the moment.', 'Some recent long-context models interleave Mamba-style layers with a few attention layers to stay fast without losing recall.', '[{"text":"One common cheap ingredient in hybrids.","id":"statespacemodel"},{"text":"The pricey-but-precise ingredient.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'Pure attention is powerful but scales badly with sequence length; alternatives like state-space models are cheaper but weaker at precise recall. Hybrids combine them — mostly cheap layers with a sprinkle of attention — to keep quality high while controlling cost on long inputs. It’s an engineering compromise that’s become popular as context windows balloon.', 'A route to long-context models that don’t blow up in cost or latency.', 'A model interleaving heterogeneous layer types (e.g., attention and SSM) to balance cost and capability.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('retrievalaugmentedarchitecture', 'Retrieval-Augmented Architecture', '', '', ARRAY['retrievalaugmentedarchitecture','retrieval-augmented architecture']::text[], 'Core', 'A model design that builds document lookup into its structure, so it fetches facts as part of thinking, not as an afterthought.', 'Like a lawyer whose desk is wired to the law library — pulling the right case mid-sentence rather than trusting memory.', 'A support assistant that queries your help-center database on every question, then answers from what it found, is retrieval-augmented by design.', '[{"text":"The technique it’s built around.","id":"rag"},{"text":"The knowledge store it queries.","id":"nonparametricmemory"}]'::jsonb, 'Rather than cramming all knowledge into weights, these models pair a generator with a retriever that pulls relevant text at run time, keeping knowledge fresh and updatable. It’s the architectural home of RAG. The hard parts are retrieving the right chunks and blending them cleanly into generation — bad retrieval quietly poisons good generation.', 'How you keep a model current and grounded without retraining it.', 'An architecture coupling a parametric generator with a non-parametric retrieval component at inference.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('memoryaugmentednetwork', 'Memory-Augmented Network', '', '', ARRAY['memoryaugmentednetwork','memory-augmented network','memory augmented network']::text[], 'Fading', 'A network bolted onto an external memory it can read from and write to, like a scratchpad it controls.', 'Like giving someone a notebook they can jot into and flip back through, instead of forcing them to hold everything in their head.', 'Early “Neural Turing Machine” research let a network store and recall sequences using a differentiable memory bank.', '[{"text":"The modern, practical descendant of the idea.","id":"retrievalaugmentedarchitecture"}]'::jsonb, 'These architectures separate computation from storage: the network learns to write facts into an addressable memory and read them back later, in principle handling tasks that need long-term recall. They were influential research but tricky to train and were largely overtaken by big transformers with long context and retrieval. The idea of external memory lives on in RAG-style systems.', 'Mostly a research lineage now; its spirit survives in retrieval-based systems.', 'A network with a differentiable external memory supporting learned read/write operations.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('pointernetwork', 'Pointer Network', '', '', ARRAY['pointernetwork','pointer network','pointer net']::text[], 'Fading', 'A network that answers by pointing back at positions in its input rather than generating brand-new words.', 'Like answering “which of these do you want?” by pointing at items on the table instead of describing them from scratch.', 'For extractive summarization, a pointer network selects which input sentences to copy verbatim.', '[{"text":"The mechanism it repurposes to point.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'Instead of producing tokens from a fixed vocabulary, it uses attention to point at input elements, which is perfect when the answer is a selection or reordering of the input — sorting, routing, copying exact names. Modern LLMs with copy mechanisms and attention absorbed much of this capability, so pointer networks are now more of a specialized or historical tool.', 'A niche design for tasks that are really about selecting from the input.', 'A seq2seq model whose output distribution is attention over input positions.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('graphneuralnetwork', 'Graph Neural Network', 'GNN', '', ARRAY['graphneuralnetwork','graph neural network','gnn','gnns']::text[], 'Core', 'A network built for data shaped like a network — nodes and connections — that learns by passing messages between neighbors.', 'Like gossip spreading through a friend group: each person updates their view based on what their direct friends say.', 'Fraud detection systems use GNNs over transaction graphs to spot rings of accounts that look normal alone but suspicious together.', '[{"text":"The sequence-oriented alternative.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'Where transformers assume a sequence and CNNs assume a grid, GNNs assume an arbitrary graph, and each node updates itself by aggregating messages from its neighbors over several rounds. That fits molecules, social networks, and recommendation graphs naturally. They’re powerful on relational data but can struggle to pass information across very distant nodes.', 'The right tool when your data is fundamentally about connections, not sequences.', 'A network operating on graph-structured data via iterative neighborhood message passing.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('embeddinglayer', 'Embedding Layer', '', '', ARRAY['embeddinglayer','embedding layer']::text[], 'Core', 'The first layer that turns each token ID into a vector the rest of the network can actually work with.', 'Like a coat check that swaps your ticket number for the actual coat — the number meant nothing until it fetched the real thing.', 'When token #4021 for “dog” enters a model, the embedding layer looks up its learned 4,096-number vector.', '[{"text":"The vectors it produces.","id":"embeddings"},{"text":"What feeds into it.","id":"tokenization"}]'::jsonb, 'It’s essentially a big lookup table: one learned vector per vocabulary entry, trained alongside everything else. Raw token IDs are meaningless integers; the embedding layer gives each a rich numeric meaning that captures similarity and usage. Everything downstream operates on these vectors, so this humble table is where language first becomes math.', 'The unglamorous doorway where words become numbers the model can reason over.', 'A learned lookup table mapping token IDs to dense vectors, trained jointly with the model.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('outputhead', 'Output Head', '', '', ARRAY['outputhead','output head','head']::text[], 'Core', 'The final layer that converts the model’s internal thinking into the actual answer — a word, a score, a label.', 'Like the last station on an assembly line that stamps the finished product into its shippable form.', 'A language model’s output head turns its final hidden vector into a probability for every possible next word.', '[{"text":"The next-word variant of it.","id":"languagemodelinghead"},{"text":"The classification variant.","id":"classificationhead"}]'::jsonb, 'The body of the network produces a rich internal representation; the head is the task-specific piece that maps that representation to the output you want. Swap the head and you repurpose the same backbone — one head for next-word prediction, another for classification, another for a numeric score. It’s the interface between general understanding and a specific job.', 'The swappable tip that adapts one pretrained backbone to many tasks.', 'The final projection mapping hidden states to task-specific outputs (logits, labels, scalars).', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('languagemodelinghead', 'Language Modeling Head', 'LM Head', '', ARRAY['languagemodelinghead','language modeling head','lm head']::text[], 'Core', 'The output layer that turns the model’s final state into a probability for every possible next token.', 'Like a spinner over the whole dictionary, weighted so likely next words get the biggest slices.', 'When a chatbot picks its next word, the LM head produced the odds over the vocabulary that the sampler then draws from.', '[{"text":"The general concept it’s a version of.","id":"outputhead"},{"text":"What it produces.","id":"logits"}]'::jsonb, 'It projects the last hidden vector onto the full vocabulary, producing one raw score (logit) per possible token, which softmax turns into probabilities. In many models it shares weights with the embedding layer to save parameters. This head is what makes a model “generative” — everything else builds the state, this turns it into a next-word bet.', 'The component that literally decides the odds behind every generated word.', 'A linear projection from hidden state to vocabulary logits, often tied to the embedding matrix.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('classificationhead', 'Classification Head', '', '', ARRAY['classificationhead','classification head']::text[], 'Core', 'A small output layer that maps the model’s understanding to a choice among fixed categories.', 'Like the final judge at a science fair who takes all the deliberation and stamps one ribbon: first, second, or third.', 'A spam filter puts a classification head on a text encoder to output “spam” or “not spam.”', '[{"text":"The general concept it’s a version of.","id":"outputhead"},{"text":"How the input gets summarized for it.","id":"pooling"}]'::jsonb, 'It takes a pooled representation of the input and projects it to one score per class, with the highest score winning. You can bolt it onto a frozen or fine-tuned backbone to specialize a general model for a specific labeling task. It’s the standard way to turn an understanding model into a decision-maker.', 'The cheap add-on that turns a language model into a categorizer.', 'A projection from a pooled representation to per-class logits for a fixed label set.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('pooling', 'Pooling', '', '', ARRAY['pooling']::text[], 'Core', 'Squashing a whole sequence of vectors into a single vector that stands for the entire input.', 'Like summarizing a long meeting into one sentence — you collapse many points into one takeaway.', 'To classify a review, a model pools the per-word vectors into one “whole-review” vector before the classification head.', '[{"text":"The most common averaging variant.","id":"meanpooling"},{"text":"A dedicated summary-token approach.","id":"clstoken"}]'::jsonb, 'Networks produce one vector per token, but many tasks need a single representation of the entire input. Pooling combines them — by averaging, taking the max, or reading a special summary token. The method matters: averaging is robust but blurry, while a dedicated summary token can learn to focus on what counts. It’s the bridge from per-token detail to one whole-input meaning.', 'The step that turns “many word-vectors” into one thing you can score or search on.', 'An aggregation over token representations (mean/max/CLS) producing a fixed-size vector.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('meanpooling', 'Mean Pooling', '', '', ARRAY['meanpooling','mean pooling','average pooling']::text[], 'Core', 'The simplest way to summarize a sequence: just average all the token vectors together.', 'Like taking the average grade of a class to represent how the class did overall.', 'Many sentence-embedding models mean-pool a sentence’s word vectors to get one vector for search.', '[{"text":"The general operation it’s a case of.","id":"pooling"},{"text":"What it’s commonly used to build.","id":"sentenceembedding"}]'::jsonb, 'You add up every token’s vector and divide by the count, giving equal weight to each. It’s cheap, stable, and surprisingly effective for embeddings, though it can wash out a crucial word by drowning it in the average. When every token matters roughly equally, mean pooling is hard to beat for its simplicity.', 'A dependable default for turning text into one searchable vector.', 'Elementwise averaging of token vectors, often masked to ignore padding.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('clstoken', 'CLS Token', 'Classification Token', '', ARRAY['clstoken','cls token','classification token','[cls]']::text[], 'Fading', 'A special slot added to the front of the input whose final vector is trained to summarize the whole thing.', 'Like a designated note-taker who sits in on the whole meeting so you can just read their one summary afterward.', 'BERT prepends a [CLS] token and uses its output vector as the sentence representation for classification.', '[{"text":"The model that made it famous.","id":"bert"},{"text":"The broader operation it competes with.","id":"pooling"}]'::jsonb, 'You prepend a dummy token that carries no word meaning; because attention lets it look at everything, it learns during training to gather a useful summary of the whole sequence into its final vector. It’s the classic trick in encoder models like BERT. Newer decoder-only models often rely on the last token or pooling instead, so it’s fading from the spotlight.', 'A tidy way older models produced one “whole-input” vector; less common now.', 'A prepended token whose final hidden state serves as an aggregate sequence representation.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('contextparallelism', 'Context Parallelism', '', '', ARRAY['contextparallelism','context parallelism','sequence parallelism']::text[], 'Rising', 'Splitting one very long input across multiple GPUs so no single chip has to hold the whole sequence.', 'Like several people each reading a different third of a huge document, then comparing notes to understand the whole.', 'Training a model on a 1-million-token context often splits that sequence across many GPUs via context parallelism.', '[{"text":"The sibling that splits the math within a layer.","id":"tensorparallelism"},{"text":"The sibling that splits layers across devices.","id":"pipelineparallelism"}]'::jsonb, 'Attention over very long sequences needs enormous memory, more than one GPU has. Context parallelism shards the sequence dimension across devices, so each holds part of the tokens, and they exchange the pieces of attention that cross boundaries. It’s one of several parallelism strategies that make long-context and large-model training possible at all.', 'Part of the plumbing that makes million-token context windows feasible to train.', 'Sharding the sequence dimension across devices, with communication for cross-shard attention.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('tensorparallelism', 'Tensor Parallelism', '', '', ARRAY['tensorparallelism','tensor parallelism']::text[], 'Core', 'Splitting a single layer’s math across several GPUs so they compute one big matrix multiply together.', 'Like four cashiers ringing up different halves of one giant order at the same time, then combining the totals.', 'Serving a model too big for one GPU often splits each layer’s weight matrices across 4 or 8 GPUs.', '[{"text":"The broader family of splitting techniques.","id":"modelparallelism"},{"text":"The sibling that splits layers instead.","id":"pipelineparallelism"}]'::jsonb, 'Within a layer, the big weight matrices are chopped into pieces spread across GPUs; each computes its slice and the results are combined with fast interconnect communication. It lets a model whose weights don’t fit on one chip run across several as if it were one. The cost is heavy inter-GPU chatter, so it wants very fast links between the chips.', 'A core reason big models need tightly-networked multi-GPU servers to run.', 'Partitioning weight matrices within layers across devices, with all-reduce/all-gather to combine.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('pipelineparallelism', 'Pipeline Parallelism', '', '', ARRAY['pipelineparallelism','pipeline parallelism']::text[], 'Core', 'Putting different layers of the model on different GPUs, like stations on an assembly line.', 'Like a car factory where each station adds one part — the car moves down the line and every station stays busy on a different vehicle.', 'A 100-layer model might put layers 1–25 on GPU A, 26–50 on GPU B, and so on, passing activations along.', '[{"text":"The broader family it belongs to.","id":"modelparallelism"},{"text":"The sibling that splits within a layer.","id":"tensorparallelism"}]'::jsonb, 'The model is cut into consecutive stages, each on its own device, and data flows through them in sequence. To keep every stage busy rather than idle-waiting, batches are split into micro-batches that flow through in a staggered pipeline. The tricky bit is the “bubble” of idle time at the start and end, which good scheduling minimizes.', 'One of the standard ways to spread a model too large for a single GPU.', 'Partitioning layers into sequential stages across devices, overlapped via micro-batching.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('modelparallelism', 'Model Parallelism', '', '', ARRAY['modelparallelism','model parallelism']::text[], 'Core', 'Spreading one model across many GPUs when it’s simply too big to fit on a single chip.', 'Like a mural too large for one wall, painted across several walls that together make the whole picture.', 'A frontier model with hundreds of billions of parameters can’t fit on one GPU, so it’s split with model parallelism.', '[{"text":"A within-layer form.","id":"tensorparallelism"},{"text":"An across-layer form.","id":"pipelineparallelism"}]'::jsonb, 'It’s the umbrella term for dividing a model’s parameters and computation across devices, whether by splitting within layers (tensor), across layers (pipeline), or across the sequence (context). It contrasts with data parallelism, where each GPU holds a full copy and just processes different examples. Modern training stacks combine several of these at once.', 'The general reason frontier models demand racks of interconnected GPUs.', 'Distributing model parameters/compute across devices; contrast with data parallelism.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('attentionsink', 'Attention Sink', '', '', ARRAY['attentionsink','attention sink','attention sinks']::text[], 'Rising', 'The odd habit models have of dumping spare attention onto the very first token, using it as a parking spot.', 'Like a conversation where everyone reflexively glances at the person at the head of the table, whether or not they’re relevant.', 'Researchers found that keeping the first few tokens in the cache preserves quality in long streaming generation — because they’re acting as sinks.', '[{"text":"The mechanism where it emerges.","id":"attention"},{"text":"The cache these tokens must stay in.","id":"kvcache"}]'::jsonb, 'Attention weights must sum to one, so when a token has nothing important to focus on, the model learns to offload that leftover attention somewhere harmless — usually the first token. Understanding this fixed a real bug: naively dropping early tokens in long conversations wrecked models until people realized those tokens were load-bearing sinks. It’s a small quirk with outsized practical impact.', 'An obscure detail that quietly governs whether long, streaming chats stay coherent.', 'The tendency of softmax attention to allocate residual mass to initial tokens, aiding long-context stability.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('longcontextarchitecture', 'Long-Context Architecture', '', '', ARRAY['longcontextarchitecture','long-context architecture','long context model']::text[], 'Rising', 'Design choices that let a model read hundreds of thousands of tokens without its cost or memory exploding.', 'Like redesigning a library so you can pull from a whole wing at once, not just the shelf beside your desk.', 'Models that accept an entire codebase or a long book in one prompt rely on long-context architecture tricks.', '[{"text":"The failure it fights against.","id":"lostinthemiddle"},{"text":"A cheaper attention pattern it may use.","id":"slidingwindowattention"}]'::jsonb, 'Plain attention cost grows with the square of the sequence length, so naively long contexts become impossibly expensive. Long-context designs use sparse or windowed attention, better positional schemes, cheaper layer types, and specialized caching to keep it tractable. The hard part isn’t just fitting the tokens — it’s making the model actually use information buried in the middle.', 'What lets your product paste in whole documents instead of chunking everything.', 'Architectural techniques (sparse attention, position schemes, caching) mitigating quadratic attention cost.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('sparsemixture', 'Sparse Mixture', 'Sparse Mixture of Experts', '', ARRAY['sparsemixture','sparse mixture','sparse moe']::text[], 'Rising', 'A mixture-of-experts model where only a few experts fire per token, keeping a giant model cheap to run.', 'Like a huge consulting firm where any one question only pulls in two specialists, not the entire staff.', 'A model with 100 billion total parameters but only 12 billion active per token is a sparse mixture.', '[{"text":"The general model class.","id":"mixtureofexperts"},{"text":"The always-on opposite.","id":"densetransformer"}]'::jsonb, '“Sparse” means each token activates just a small subset of the experts, so total capacity can be enormous while per-token compute stays modest. This decouples a model’s knowledge (total params) from its running cost (active params). The trade-offs are memory to hold all the experts and the routing quality that decides which few actually run.', 'How a model can be “huge” in capability yet still affordable per token.', 'An MoE with top-k expert activation, decoupling total from active parameters.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('densetransformer', 'Dense Transformer', '', '', ARRAY['densetransformer','dense transformer','dense architecture']::text[], 'Core', 'The classic transformer where every token passes through every parameter — no experts, no skipping.', 'Like a restaurant where every dish goes through the entire kitchen staff, not a specialized station.', 'Most well-known models before the mixture-of-experts wave were dense transformers.', '[{"text":"The sparse alternative.","id":"sparsemixture"},{"text":"The architecture it’s a form of.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'In a dense model, all weights are active for every token, so compute per token scales directly with model size. It’s simpler to train and reason about than sparse mixtures, with no routing to get wrong, but it can’t grow its knowledge without paying full price on every token. It’s the baseline against which sparse designs are measured.', 'The straightforward, predictable model shape — capability and cost rise together.', 'A transformer with all parameters active per token; contrast with sparse MoE.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('encoderonly', 'Encoder-Only', '', '', ARRAY['encoderonly','encoder-only','encoder only']::text[], 'Fading', 'A transformer that only reads and understands text — no generation half at all.', 'Like a book reviewer who deeply understands a manuscript but was never hired to write one.', 'BERT is the poster child: brilliant at classification and search, incapable of writing a paragraph.', '[{"text":"The canonical example.","id":"bert"},{"text":"The generation-focused opposite.","id":"gptarchitecture"}]'::jsonb, 'It keeps only the encoder stack, reading the whole input at once (bidirectionally) to build rich representations, and is trained by predicting masked-out words. That makes it strong and cheap for understanding tasks but unable to generate freely. As generative chat models took over, encoder-only fell out of fashion, though it still powers plenty of search and embedding work.', 'A lean, fast choice when you only need to understand or classify, not generate.', 'A transformer using only the encoder stack, trained bidirectionally for representation tasks.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('bidirectionalmodel', 'Bidirectional Model', '', '', ARRAY['bidirectionalmodel','bidirectional model','bidirectional']::text[], 'Fading', 'A model that reads each word using context from both its left and its right at the same time.', 'Like understanding a pun only after you’ve read the whole sentence, not word by word as it arrives.', 'To fill in “the ___ barked,” a bidirectional model uses “barked” on the right to guess “dog.”', '[{"text":"The one-directional counterpart.","id":"causallanguagemodel"},{"text":"The task it’s trained with.","id":"maskedlanguagemodel"}]'::jsonb, 'Because it sees the full sentence at once, it can use future words to interpret earlier ones, which is great for understanding but incompatible with left-to-right generation. That’s why bidirectional models like BERT dominate comprehension tasks while generative chatbots use one-directional (causal) attention. The direction of attention is the whole difference.', 'Superb for understanding tasks; structurally unable to generate text on its own.', 'A model with unmasked attention, conditioning each position on the full sequence.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('causallanguagemodel', 'Causal Language Model', '', '', ARRAY['causallanguagemodel','causal language model','causal lm']::text[], 'Core', 'A model that can only look leftward — predicting each word from the words before it, never after.', 'Like writing a story with a card covering everything you haven’t written yet — you decide the next word from what’s already on the page.', 'Every generative chatbot is a causal LM: it produces text one token at a time, each based only on what came before.', '[{"text":"The masking that enforces it.","id":"causalattention"},{"text":"The both-directions opposite.","id":"bidirectionalmodel"}]'::jsonb, '“Causal” means the attention is masked so a token can attend to earlier positions but not future ones, which is exactly what lets the model generate text left to right. It’s the standard setup for GPT-style models. The constraint is also its power: by never peeking ahead, it can be trained on plain text and then generate coherently.', 'The default shape of any model that writes, chats, or completes text.', 'A model with causal (left-to-right) attention masking, trained on next-token prediction.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('maskedlanguagemodel', 'Masked Language Model', 'MLM', '', ARRAY['maskedlanguagemodel','masked language model','mlm']::text[], 'Fading', 'A training trick where you hide random words and make the model guess them from the words around them.', 'Like a fill-in-the-blank exercise — “The cat sat on the ___” — where you deduce the answer from the rest.', 'BERT was trained by masking about 15% of words in each sentence and predicting each one.', '[{"text":"The model type it trains.","id":"bert"},{"text":"The generative training objective it contrasts with.","id":"nexttokenprediction"}]'::jsonb, 'By blanking out tokens and asking the model to recover them using both left and right context, MLM teaches deep bidirectional understanding without needing labeled data. It’s the training objective behind encoder models, but it doesn’t naturally produce a text generator. Next-token prediction won out for generative models precisely because it does.', 'The learning recipe behind understanding-focused models, not chatbots.', 'A self-supervised objective predicting masked tokens from bidirectional context.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('prefixlm', 'Prefix LM', 'Prefix Language Model', '', ARRAY['prefixlm','prefix lm','prefix language model']::text[], 'Fading', 'A hybrid that reads the prompt with full both-directions attention but then generates the answer left to right.', 'Like studying a question from every angle before you start writing your essay strictly top to bottom.', 'Some instruction-tuned models let the whole prompt attend freely, then switch to causal mode for the response.', '[{"text":"The generate-only counterpart.","id":"causallanguagemodel"},{"text":"The understand-only counterpart.","id":"bidirectionalmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'It splits the sequence: the prefix (input) uses bidirectional attention so the model understands it fully, while the continuation (output) uses causal attention so it can be generated. This aims to combine strong comprehension of the prompt with the ability to generate. It sits between pure encoder-decoder and pure decoder-only designs, and stayed a niche as decoder-only models dominated.', 'A middle-ground design; most products just use plain decoder-only models instead.', 'A model applying bidirectional attention over the prefix and causal attention over the continuation.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('speculativearchitecture', 'Speculative Architecture', 'Speculative Decoding', '', ARRAY['speculativearchitecture','speculative architecture','speculative decoding']::text[], 'Rising', 'A speed trick where a tiny fast model guesses several next words and a big model just checks them in one pass.', 'Like a junior drafts a few sentences and the senior editor approves or fixes them in a single quick read — faster than the senior writing every word.', 'A serving stack might use a small draft model to propose 4 tokens, then have the big model verify all 4 at once.', '[{"text":"The small model doing the guessing.","id":"draftmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'The big model normally makes tokens one slow step at a time. Here a cheap draft model proposes a short run of tokens, and the big model verifies them in parallel, accepting the ones it agrees with and correcting at the first disagreement. Output is identical to the big model alone, just produced faster — pure latency savings with no quality loss.', 'A way to make responses noticeably faster and cheaper with no drop in answer quality.', 'Parallel verification of a small draft model’s proposed tokens by the target model, preserving its distribution.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('draftmodel', 'Draft Model', '', '', ARRAY['draftmodel','draft model','drafter']::text[], 'Rising', 'The small, fast model that proposes candidate next words for a bigger model to check.', 'Like an intern who quickly sketches the next few lines so the expert only has to review, not write from scratch.', 'In speculative decoding, a 1-billion-parameter draft model guesses tokens that a 70-billion-parameter model then verifies.', '[{"text":"The technique it powers.","id":"speculativearchitecture"}]'::jsonb, 'It needs to be fast and roughly agree with the big model, since every token the big model rejects is wasted draft work. The closer the draft’s guesses match the target, the more speedup you get. Choosing or training a good draft model — fast enough to help, aligned enough to be accepted — is the core engineering knob of speculative decoding.', 'The cheap helper that makes the expensive model respond faster.', 'A lightweight model proposing tokens for parallel verification by the target model.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('moerouting', 'MoE Routing', '', '', ARRAY['moerouting','moe routing','mixture-of-experts routing']::text[], 'Rising', 'The overall strategy for deciding which experts each token visits and keeping the load balanced across them.', 'Like a dispatcher assigning delivery jobs to drivers — route by expertise, but don’t leave some drivers idle and others swamped.', 'A model card might report “top-2 routing with a load-balancing loss” to describe its MoE routing scheme.', '[{"text":"The component that executes it.","id":"routernetwork"},{"text":"The model class it serves.","id":"sparsemixture"}]'::jsonb, 'Routing covers both the per-token choice (which top-k experts) and the system-level concern of spreading tokens evenly so no expert is overwhelmed or neglected. Poor routing causes wasted capacity, unstable training, and “dead” experts. Techniques like auxiliary balancing losses and capacity limits exist mostly to keep routing healthy at scale.', 'The design detail that decides whether a sparse model’s promised efficiency actually materializes.', 'The policy and losses governing top-k expert selection and load balancing in MoE layers.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[])
